    {"title": "Mismatched Monthly Allocation Divisors Cause Final Investor Claims to Revert Due to Truncation Deficit", "description": "Root cause & mechanism\nThe investor onboarding logic in add_investor_to_category misaligns (1) the category-level \u201creservation/refill rate\u201d used to grow the amount considered reserved for investor claims and (2) the investor-level monthly claim rate used by investor_claim_tokens. This happens because, when an investor is treated as joining mid-vesting, the function converts one month of vesting into an extra 1-month cliff (to \u201cskip the remainder of the first month\u201d since adding happens half-way through a cycle) by:\n- setting investor.cliff_months_remaining = 1\n- decrementing investor.vesting_months_remaining by 1\n\nBut it then updates category.total_allocated_tokens_monthly using total_allocation_in_base_units divided by (investor.vesting_months_remaining + 1) (i.e., the original remaining vesting-month count before the decrement), while computing investor.monthly_allocation_in_base_units using total_allocation_in_base_units divided by investor.vesting_months_remaining (i.e., the reduced month count after the decrement). Both are integer (floor) divisions. Splitting the same total across two different divisors causes a systematic rounding mismatch.\n\nThis mismatch propagates into category-level accounting:\n- tokens_ready_for_claim (the value intended to represent tokens that must remain in the category ATA to satisfy investor claims, and which is used as the upper limit for manual category withdrawal) is increased during category vesting updates (update_vesting_for_investor_category) using:\n  category.tokens_ready_for_claim += category.total_allocated_tokens_monthly * vesting_months_claimed\n- Because total_allocated_tokens_monthly is understated for late-joined investors, tokens_ready_for_claim grows too slowly relative to what those investors will later claim.\n\nAdditionally, for mid-vesting joins the code implicitly relies on \u201chistorical\u201d vested tokens already sitting in the category ATA (from months before the investor was added) to cover part of the shortfall, but those historical balances are never reserved in tokens_ready_for_claim, breaking its intended meaning.\n\nA further logic error broadens when the buggy \u201cmid-vesting\u201d branch is taken: the branch condition checks only investor.cliff_months_remaining == 0 && investor.vesting_months_remaining > 0 and does not verify that TGE/vesting has started (category.cliff_started_at != 0). Therefore, in categories configured with no cliff, investors added before TGE can be incorrectly treated as mid-vesting joiners and forced into the same synthetic-cliff + mismatched-divisor path.\n\nTrigger conditions / assumptions\n- Mid-vesting / late join path is taken when investor.cliff_months_remaining == 0 && investor.vesting_months_remaining > 0 at onboarding.\n  - Common case: the category cliff has ended and the category is actively vesting.\n  - In non-local-testing builds, onboarding is only allowed when the category is \u201cup to date\u201d (full_months_since_last_claim must be 0, else ErrorCode::CategoryLevelUnclaimed), meaning the investor can be added only when there are no unclaimed category-level months pending.\n- The erroneous pre-TGE trigger occurs when:\n  - category.cliff_months_remaining == 0 (no cliff category),\n  - category.cliff_started_at == 0 (TGE not started),\n  - category.vesting_months_remaining > 0,\n  causing the same mid-vesting penalty logic to execute despite no vesting cycles having started.\n- The rounding mismatch is most apparent for allocations where floor(Total / V) * V differs from floor(Total / (V-1)) * (V-1). One described sufficient condition: total_allocation % V < total_allocation % (V + 1) (where V is the reduced vesting-month count), which makes category accumulation strictly less than investor entitlement.\n- SPL Token transfers are all-or-nothing on insuffi